    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-04-29T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-04-29T00:00:00-05:00" n="415"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d415">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00116 European War 1939/921</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum of Telephone Conversation, by the Adviser on
                        Political Relations</hi> (<hi rend="italic">Dunn</hi>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-04-29">April 29,
                            1943</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Admiral Leahy<note n="10" xml:id="d415fn10">Adm. William D. Leahy, Chief of Staff
                        to the Commander in Chief of the Army and Navy.</note> telephoned me this
                    morning and said that he had taken up with the President the note we had from
                    the British Embassy informing us of Prime Minister Churchill’s statement on the
                    possible use of poison gas by the Germans. Admiral Leahy said that the President
                    felt that in view of the Prime Minister’s statement it would serve no useful
                    purpose for the President to take any action along these lines at present.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">James Clement Dunn</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
